I agree with the opinion that high schools impose on students for attending a certain amount of volunteer work in order to graduate.
Because students can grow up through volunteer work experiences.
Of course I know some objections that it is far away from its essence to make students take part in volunteer work as a requirement of graduation.
It is the best to do it from his spontaneous volunteer spirit.
But why schools dare to do so is that they have ceatain thoughts that volunteer work is definitely good for student's life.
When I was in high school, I took part in volunteer work as a kindergarden teacher.
It was very fun to play with kids.
But I felt a kind of defficulties.
And I thought that it was quite taugh that smiling all the day as a professional. Generally the salary of kindergarden teacher is not high.
I really felt their professional spirits and their job ethics.
To experience the outside of your world through volunteer work you can realize how small your place which usually live in is.
The discovery is the most precious for you.
There is a saying in Japan; No matter how much you may spend money, you should experience various defficulties or trouble .
A experience is a tresure.
I think it is good for students that schools have a requirement that students must complete a certain amount of volunteer work in order to graduate.
Because it may be a trigger to realize something.
In the contemporary society, volunteer certificate is considered as a compulsory requirement for students to graduate in some high school, which remains a highly continuous public discourse.
I strongly believe that although many benefits that this trend has brought to students, its drawbacks should not be ignored.
On the one hand, volunteer work plays an essential role in helping youngster not only develop their social relationship but also become more active and sympathy.
Nowadays, adolescent live in a close- knit family with high standard of living, so some of them might not understand how difficult the poor have to experience.
Becoming a volunteer will get youngster out of their comfort vibe because they have a chance to do something that they have never done before to help the elderly, the disabled,...
such as collecting old stuff, raising fund, teaching disabled children at orphanage,...
Thanks to these activities, students can broaden their mind and know how to get well on with other people, no matter where they are from.
Moreover, teenagers also become more empathy to their parents and appreciate for the time all members live together.
The Green Summer is a good illustration for volunteer work in Viet Nam, which attracts millions of students every year with many unforgetable experience.
On the other hand, those whose argument revolves around the disadvantages of obligatory volunteer certificate might contend that students can only receive real value when they participate in volunteering without be required.
It is undeniable that some volunteers feel exhausted after doing volunteer work and they just think about graduate certificate, in lieu of precious value from volunteering thereby not able to focusing on helping communities.
As the result, helping communities to get ovet the obstacles in life indeliberately become a tedious task for youngster, instead of an useful work for developing both knowledge and positive personality.
In conclusion, the rise of compulsory volunteer has both advantages and disadvantages.
From a personal perspective, the aforementioned reasons lay an adequate foundation for me to believe that the downsides of this trend outweighs its upsides and more encouragement should be made by school and society to interest students in volunteer work.
