Some schools oblige their students to study music and to play a musical instrument.
For example, in France every students from 10 to 14 years old are taking music classes two hours a week.
Other countries do not have the politics and young people wouldn't learn about music.
In my opinion students should have to study music but not learn how to play a musical instrument.
Of course, studying music and learning how to play a musical instrument can help students to develop creativity and amusment.
As any art, music have the power to be universal and everyone can enjoy some of it.
Learning about music will open the mind of young students, and they will discover another kind of culture, or re-enforce what they already know.
Studiying music can have many aspects as reading the music or learning about former famous singers or musicians, or even singing some songs.
Some students might discover a new hobbie, and as it happened to me, to study music outisde the walls of shcool.
Playing a musical instrument can be more difficult to organise.
Most musical instruments are very expensive, and most shcools can not afford such an expense.
I belive if only rich schools can make it happen it will worsen inequalities between students, and in the society in general.
Of course, if the state is funding all the equipment I believe every student should learn a musical instrument because it will give them new skills and open even more their mind to art and music culture.
Some people say if you have plenty of money, you can buy anything you want.
This statement is partly true, but being healthy is what you cannot buy with money.
Suppose you have terminal cancer.
No matter how much money you have, any treatment you can afford today may not able to cure it.
For example, Steve Jobs, one of the co-founders of Apple, was extremely wealthy, but he died of pancreas cancer.
Money cannot always deal with health problems.
That said, being rich enables you to beef up your health.
It costs you a decent amount of money to eat healthy food, to get regular check-ups, and receive medical treatment.
I think that though being healthy is more important than being rich, being healthy requires being rich, at least not poor.
