Many people consider truthfulness as a very positive virtue.
I also believe that, yet I dare to say that under some specific circumstances it is better to tell a lie.
Firstly we need to determine why we lie.
By doing so we can hide inconvienent facts about ourselves or we also can avoid being punished for things that we have done.
For short amount of time lying might even be beneficial for us, however when the truth is revealed we often get much bigger predicament than we would have if we had not lied.
Another consequence of lying is that people could start perceive us as dishonest and unreliable person.
This obviously aggravates our relationships with friends or acquintances.
Lastly, not telling truth is considered as sin by most religions in the world so if we do so, it will be against our beliefs and conscience.
I see only one exception in which we are justified to tell a lie.
That is when we gain nothing for ourselves and by telling truth we would cause pain to other person.
I can give example of such a lie from literature.
There is a book called "Kamizelka" written by Boles\u0142aw Prus.
The novel depicts history of a mariage, in which husband is terminally ill.
He is losing uncontrollably weight so in order no to worry his wife he notoriously shortens his vest's bands.
To summarise, I think there are conditions under which we can lie, but normally I strongly believe that it is better to just tell the truth.
Making volunteer work obligatory for high schools students would not in my honest opinion bring positive results.
Main purpose of school is to teach students various subjects and prepare them for their final exams.
I believe that this is a period of time in which we need to really focus on our education.
From my personal expierence I can tell that there are pupils who actually learn a lot on their own and who take part in many competitions, which consumes most of their free time.
I am completely convinced that if volunteer work was required from them, they would become distracted and extremely tired so that they might not have achieved as much as they wanted.
The second drawback of compulsory volunteer work is the fact that it might be perceive as a duty or errand.
If something is compulsory, we usually tend not to like such thing.
I think people who willingly participate in such kind of work can gain expierence or help others.
However if someone is not kin for such thing, then it will be only a burden for them.
Volunteer work might also collide with some extracurricural activities of some students.
In such situation they would need to resign from their interests.
Some people might as well consider work just as a way of earning money, therefore they would have even more reasons to dislike the idea of volunteer work.
To summarise, volunteer work can be beneficial for some people, but making it obligatory for everyone is pointless.
in order to develop any task humans need to gather a wide range of skills which are adopted during our lifetime, therefore, practise is completely required when it comes to adquiring abilities.
It is known that the more skills that we have, the more tools to solve a problem or hard situation are available.
On the one hand, my careeer is highly related to human beigns, as far as I am concerned, no matter how physically fit or strong we are, every activity we do is absolutely related to our core "computer" which is our unbelievable clever brain.
What is more, the childhood and the begining of the teenage are the most esential moments for its proper development.
In addition of taking care of it by protecting from strong hits and holding an adequate alimentation and the right amount of sleep, there is a pattern which is crucial, it is called "mind sharp," basically means, brain training.
When the first studies on this field appeared, almost every school took wonderful policies with the aim of encouraging children to take up habits which put their minds in motion.
Commonly, most primary schools introduced music to their basic studies, nevertheless, some high quality learning institutes have taken up stunning activities such as theathre, phylosophy, farming and so on.
Believe it or not, the world of education is witnessing a revolution on the way that children are taught.
Contrary to the antique beliefs of learning everything by heart, the new systems gives extreme priority to team work, leadership, entrepreneurship and critical thinking among many other skills marvellously useful for the adult lives of the future generations.
To sum up, the government has endorsed these practises by raising the educational budgets looking forward to seeing the first changes in society withing the next fifteen years.
