The point is "salary."
Doctors working in cities earn a lot but those who working in rural areas earn less.
This problem is more intricating than we think.
You may think that all the doctor should take a same amount of salary.
However, the salary depends on the amount of patients.
The city doctors work much harder than dispensary doctors due to the quantity of patients.
This means city doctors earn much money than those who working in rural areas.
Therefore, the point is not only "salary," but also "how busy their job is."
No one can control the population, thus the solution is not easy.
One of my suggestion is, implementation of "doctor helicopters."
Huge hospitals are constructed near rural areas, substantial medical equipments are there, and adequate doctors are working there.
Those hospitals possess some helicopters for emargency patients living in rural areas.
It might be huge amount of cost to hold helicopters, however the amount of patients in collected rural areas are increased eventually.
The salary would be pretty much same.
