For start I would like to say that the volunteer work is really helpfull and people should do it in generall but the question is whether the schools should require it from their students.
To put it another way this work is calls a volunteer work which means that the people should not be forced to it.
In other words the students should decide themselves whether they want to help without the pressure from the school.
In my opinion are the people which are forced to do something not really happy and they dont do it properly.
I am convinced that the schools should support their students to participate on these types of volunteer work and they should probably have some benefits for the student who actually do that.
And most importantly when someone requires the volunteer work it is no longer voluntary which is the essence of this kind of work.
Working in an office means, for most people, stability.
This is certainly due to a defined work timing and to a long-term planning of activities, both personal and of the workteam, both on the workative side, as the projects to get to term, and on the private side, as the vacation period.
Moreover, a job office offers the chance to have a personal space which no one else is allowed to touch: a desk.
Having a private desk, in which organizing files as we think is best, can really make the difference on our productivity.
However, there are a lot of different types of desks.
In some offices employees work locked in cubicles, with empty walls and no chance to personalise their locations, neither attaching photos on the walls nor putting little plants on the desks.
This denied personalisation could have negative consequences on employees productivity: they are supposed to spend all their work time sitting alone, in front of their computers, avoiding every human interactions.
In this way workers are isolated and they can't neither exchange their ideas nor spend a word to interrupt the routine.
On the opposite, an open space allows emplyees to talk to each other, to act like a group escaping the isolation in which cubicles would force them.
In this way, the job gets to be more dynamic and ideas can develop easier.
If workers had the opportunity to personalize their desks too, their productivity would be, out of any doubt, much bigger, because they would work in a place they feel hoomy.
Dear Sir or Madam of our town council, I am writing to you this letter regarding to your idea of banning the use of mobile phones on public transports.
I am a citizen of the city and would like to tell you my opinion according to this issue.
First of all, I would like to tell you that I may understand why you want to ban the mobile phones.
A lot of accidents, which have been happened, happened because people used their mobile phones in the traffic and for surre: that is danger.
According to the number of accidents, I would counsel you to ban it.
But nevertheless we cannot overview the other aspects.
As you know, mobile phones has become pretty important in the last decade.
There is a great digitalization and at the moment you could do almost everything in internet.
Do not forget that there are people who are buying their tickets in an online-shop.
These tickets are not printed but on there mobile phones.
At least in that parts mobile phones are not only useful but necessary.
Moreover a lot of people hear music during the wait-time for their transport or in the transports.
As I said in the beginning, it may be dangerous but I think instead of banning mobile phones, it might be better to invest in warnings because through banning you limit the freedom of the people.
It is the same in restaurants and shops.
It is a limitation which are not necessary and will annoy the people.
So I would like to ask that you just leave it.
Kind regards, Anna
Globalization has, as inevitable consequences, the increasing of the population in the cities - especially in the city centres - and the decreasing of the number of people who live in rural areas.
Theese two factors inevitably conduced to a huger concentrarion of the services, including those which are considered of first necessity - in the cities.
As always happens, everyone sfrutted the thing on their own advantages, even doctors, who are supposed to be charital and altruistical people.
On the contrary, most of them revealed to be interested much more in money and success instead in people's health.
First of all, doctors shouldn't be allowed to gain all the money they gain, because they are supposed to do their job because of a vocation they have inside them.
Secondly, they shouldn't be allowed to have three, four or five jobs in different structures, a solution which would also solving part of the disocupation problem.
Thirdly, they shouldn't have the possibility to conduce private visits in public hospital structures.
Here, in Italy, this process is called "intramenia."
On the other side, the problem of less and less people in rural zones should be solved with ripopulationing campaignes.
It's obvious that in a village with three or four living people can't stay everyday a doctor: it would be a waste of public money, which we really need to save and spend accurately.
