Some employers think that working in separating and specified spaces are better than open offices.
In my opinion, it dependes on the type of work and job that company is doing.
If the work done by employees is demandeing deep focus therefore shared office is not a good idea.
The distraction caused by others will drain the employees concentration and the quality of work will be low.
For example, in a programming office, the workers need a silent environment though they can focus on their codes, and a noisy place or a place full of momvemnt will not let them to centralize on their work.
On the other hand, some type of works need a sharing office since contacting with other colleagues during the work time will generate more ideas and can birngs the creativity between coworkers.
Furthermore, some of projects are defiend to be done in a team and the open design offices can make the results more effecitve as the team members are constantely in touch with each other and all the team know the progrees of the project and what will be the next step.
