One of the main skills to develop nowadays is related to being able to communicate properly, this skill no only involves to master your own language, but includes to learn several languages.
This is specially important in toodlers as it is well known that the ability to learn another language is developed in human brains from early years.
For that reason, parents invest a lot of money in their children education, mainly in bilingual programs.
In fact, there are many surveys that correlate learning a foreing language with better opportunities in the future.
In a world connected by internet, there will have always a demand for learning new languages as it is posible.
Moreover, today more than in the past, to dominate many languages as posible is a key factor to having a successful career.
For that reason, there are huge demand on online learning language and language teachers, as well as online resources.
Probably, today more than ever, we have a demand to learning language, and because of the advantages of the technology, we dont have more excuses for not undertake this demand.
Volunteer work is a type of activity that enabled to realize many good actions towards people or communities around the world.
In order to graduate, some high schools ask their students to achieve certain amount of volunteer work such as donating blood, becoming a leader in a youth club, facilitating art workshops, being a positive role model for a young person, and many more.
Many students respond positively to this requirement otherwise others see this demand like a loud and additional charge.
For many students this kind of work enable them to see a new horizons and discover their capacities.
It is also an occasion for students to explore a new social as well as politic issues that impacting our world.
In my opinion, schools shouldn\u2019t impose like this requirement because volunteer work must remain volunteer; furthermore, to graduate on school should be the result of personal effort for each student not conditioned by other activities.
