Music had enormous impact on our lives throughtout history, therefore some people claim that it should be taught at school and even students should be obliged to learn to play a musical instrument.
In my humble opinion that would not be beneficial to everyone, so such lessons ought not to be obligatory.
It seems to me that the most crucial role of school cirruculum is to give children vast knowledge of most important subject like mathematics or biology.
Having said that, I am not completely convinced that music is such a subject.
I think that students choose to spend their time on other activities, which might turn out to be more useful to them.
Futhermore, some people may not even like to learn playing a instrument.
For that reason, they might start to perceive those music lessons as some type of chores and as a result they would learn very ineffectively.
Moreover, no one would agrue that learning how to play a musical instrument correctly takes even years so again that would consume quite a large part of students' free time, which they might use in more beneficial way.
To top off, I strongly believe that studing music ought not to be compulsory for everyone.
I agree on the other hand that if some students want to attend additional music classess, then they should have this possibility.
Studying at a university undoubtedly brings a lot of changes to people's lives.
Some students even start to live on their own, while others stay with their family at home.
In my huble opinion, both options have some advantages as well as drawbacks.
On the one hand, by living on your own you can, without a doubt, obtain useful practical skills or expierence.
Moreover, you, for sure, will become more adult and independent.
What is more, moving out of your family home to other city might give you possibility to attend to more prestigious university.
That may particulary concern students who live in small cities or on the countryside.
On the other hand, staying at your family home is probably in all cases much less expensive than this other alternative, bacause you do not need to worry about the cost of accommodation.
Additionally, unless you stay at home, it might be neccesary to take up a part-time job to earn some money in order to pay for your new house or for meals.
Furthermore, some students might not feel comfortable in other city with lots of unfamiliar people and that might need support of their family.
For them it may be more convienent not to move out.
To top off, it seems to me that we all, sooner or later, will move out from our family house.
For that reason, I believe that not staying at home is far better option, especially if you want to attend a university which is not situated in your town.
