With current pace of life in this generation, an activity that support living stationary is contineously rising from the existence of technology and all the service that attempt to obtain profit from our laziness.
As a result thereof, do we need to encourage more active lifestyle by enforcing mandatory sporting class in school curriculum?
I fully disgree regarding this question, and two reasons are accounted for this.
Firstly, every student possess their own time schedule which is vary and different in each person.
Including three classes of sport in each week can possibly consume excessive amount of time that one can utilise in the way that is beneficial for their living.
For example, some student may need to be a part timer in order to gain enough money for their tuition; or give every vacant timeslot possible to their valuable can be a case for some as one of my friends whom her mother has an alzheimer's disease that try to reduce the cost of hiring nurse for her mother.
Secondly, although one decide to not doing any sport, this does not guarantee that one have an inactive life since several activities can do this duty in lieu.
Gardening, houseworking, or grocery shopping are considered as activities that demonstrate the usage of large amount of energy and the increase of human stamina.
Instead of compel student to do sport, which can possibly lead to a hatred in sporting, if educational institution recommend an activity that can potentially incorporate with student daily life for an improved active lifestyle such as using stairs instead of elevator, this may be a more appropriate choice for many.
To summarise, why mandatory sport class, personally, expresses disagreement: the existence of personal timetable and a plethora of sports-substituted activities in order to achive active lifestyle.
Learning a non-mother language is a hard work.
Even, in this generation, many artificial intelligence has been created to translate languages from around the world, personal communication skill in a foreign language is still important in our life, there are two outstanding reasons to support this idea.
Fisrt, being a multilinguist is more advantage.
Students who can speak a foreing language fluently tends to achieve better school and college.
Most people feel more comfortable communicating with us people than computers or robots; so, we would choose to communicate with one who understand us first.
Speaking in the same language, we can work faster.
Second, there are still people who cannot use other than their primary language.
Being able to communicate in a secondary language, we would be able to contact them properly.
Using language translator or dictionary wastes time.
Therefore, these are reasons why I think learning to speaking a foreign language is as important these days s it was in the past.
