Living in the twenty first century, the age of IT,all the children play video games except the poor of the poorest. Because the poor can not afford to buy video games facilities.
Video games are frowned on by parents as time-waster,and worse,some education experts think that these games corrupt the brain.
It can affect children's development and health when it is played exceedingly.
Some experts said that some young people become violent or commit extreme anti-social behaviour because of playing games.
Some children spend their times playing game alone in their own room instead of hanging out with friends.
It can affect his cognitive development unless he go out and socialize in the real world.
This can also impair his eyesight.
Contrary to the common view,video games have some positive effects when it is played moderately.
There are many types of games made for varied purposes \u2014some can be entertaining and relaxing while others can be challenging and good for learning.
Some games can improve children's development such as making decision in a short period of time and critical thinking skill.
It seems to me that parents should not forbid children playing games.
Instead they can help them enjoy video games properly and avoid problems.
Dear Mayor, Dear Membres of the Town Council, with this letter, I'd like to express my opinion about your last decision reguardin mobile phones.
I don't think it's up to yout to decide such as those things.
You can't - and moreover you shouldn't - stop people from using their mobile phones while they are on public transports or in shops and restaurants.
They can use their mobiles because they don't disturbe anyone.
Of course, the volume has to be swithced off, in order to respect everyone's space.
You should instead ban the use of mobile phones while people is walking on the streets or biking, to prevent and avoid accidents, and in places, as cinemas and theatres, where is dark and even the littlest light can disturb who we have nearby.
It's no sence ban mobile phones from public transports if people can use them just out their doors, maybe crossing the street.
Mobile phones are not the problem, people is.
You should promote campaignes which encourage people on using less their mobiles and living more in the real life, to teach them that the real world is outside their smartphones.
People don't learn with denies, but with taughts, explanations and examples.
I beg you to retrace your steps to find a better and effective solution.
Best Reguards, a citizen
