About office desing, I believe an open space is more efficent than a enclosed workstation.
To those who believe an enclosed workstation is the one who like to work in a prison type space. To me, it feels like no freedom and limited your working area in a confined space.
However, if working in an opened area, it enables people to talk freely, work freely.
Such condition enables people to come closer and work together instead of distancing themself in a cubicles space which limits the coorperation with each other.
One good example is Google.
Google has a free open environment for people to work anywhere they want.
Today they may choose to work near a park.
Then, the next day, they may choose to work near a playground.
Such freedom enables workers to have a choice.
By having a choice, there is where the imagination comes from and gives value to the company.
This is a valuable asset and could not be present in an enclosed workstations.
In a world that promotes mainly comfort and a sedentary life, sport should be a form of escaping.
Introducing more sports classes can be regarded as a solution for this problem but I do not consider that forcing students into taking them is a wise decision.
First of all, the most beneficial part of doing sport is improving health quality.
For example, in most cases children tend to spend time only on the computer and this can lead to scoliosis, obesity and other health issues.
Secondly, playing sports can have other benefits, like learning to be part of a team.
It is generally thought that being a team player is an advantage for job applications.
A good illustration of this is the structure of a interview when almost always, the employer asks you how well can you collaborate with other colleagues.
Furthermore, the current generation, known as \u201DY\u201D generation or \u201Dsnowflakes\u201D is at great susceptibility of mental health diseases.
Under these circumstances, playing sports can help children be happier.
Evidence for this is provided by the secretion during physical activities of substances that makes you feel relax and peaceful, such as serotonin and dopamine.
In addition, there is a reason to believe that sport can take the form of a hobby, hence giving students the opportunity to have a leisure activity and take a break from all the studying.
In spite of all the advantages that come from sport, I think that forcing children into doing it is wrong.
We can see this from early childhood because whenever you coerce a child into doing something, he will not want to do it.
Thus, obliging students in taking more sport classes can have a negative outcome, for instance they will drop sports for good.
Taking everything into consideration, even though physical activity has many pros, forcing that to students can result in the exact opposite.
