Leading an inactive lifestyle has many negative effects on health.
That is the reason why a proposal has ben put forth: obliging all university students and school chidren to do sports activities at least three times a week.
Is this really a good idea?
On the one hand, forcing something like this upon people is very authoritarian.
Such a law infringes on personal freedoms and bodily autnomy.
It would give the state more control in our youths personal lives and diminish their sense of personal responsibility.
With freem comes responsibility, and both of those are very important to have and properly make us of in life.
If from a young age the child has great personal atunomy, it will better learn to make use of it than if the state were to interfere.
The proposal above, were it made law, would stunt our children's ability to administer their own lifes.
On the other hand, the benefits of sports activities are so great and many that a sacrifice of some freedom may be justified.
Physical activity improves both physical and mental health, as well as cognitive abilities.
And in the context of schooling, where children are forced to do tasks anyay, it would make sense to make use of the advantages of sport.
Moreover, there are generalised benefits for the whole of society.
Healthier people get sick less and live longer, puttin overall less strain on the public healthcare system.
This saves costs, sicne treatment is very expensive, a lot more than prevention in the form of sports activities.
This saves taxpayers and the governemnt loads of money.
All in al, the benefits of forcing our youth to do sport outweight any possible objections.
They are already obligated to a variety of tasks in school, and adding sport to that would only have benefits.
In my opinion if the group feel comfortable with a specific teacher and the results are satisfactory, then, the best option is maintain the teacher with the same students.
