Books and technology Regarding whether computers and tablets should completely replace books in schools and universities, the answers differ among people.
Some agree with this view, and they argue that Learning with computers and tablets are more efficient and eco-friendly.
The increase of learning with laptops will reduce the usage of papers and therefore the damage to the forests.
Furthermore, it is much comfortable to take the laptops than heavy books around.
Finally, it is also much practical to store the important files on the cloud and it can be reached without location restrictions While others oppose this opinion and they state that they are more used to learn with books and do exercise with pens.
As it showed in several studies, students who learn with laptops and/or tablets have worse performance on average than students who haven't.
It is difficult for many students to focus on learning with computers without being distracted by other entertainments online.
Additionally, computers and tablets are much too expensive for many students that they cannot afford it.
Eventually, it is quite often to lose the important digital files, if they were not saved.
However, the crucial word of this argument is whether computers and tablets should 'completely' replace books in schools and universities.
Since both ways of learning have its conveniences and drawbacks, It is not reasonable to replace one with the other completely.
Because the financial situation and preference differs among people, everyone should make his own choice with regard to this question.
There are many aspects to consider when deciding which conditions would be more effective and reliable for employees who are working in offices.
Among theses, are the privacy and comfort, the specific activity or job they perform and the level of isolation their job requiers.
Firstly, it is undeniable that employees, as well as everyone else, need their own space with a comfortable and private atmosphere so they can feel less pressured.
As a result, I think that an exceedingly open design might pose a challenge for most of them.
On the other hand, what specific activity or job they are performing its also a relevant point to consider.
Whether they work on their own, individually, they are co-workers or they do these activities in groups, it must be kept in mind since it would undoubtedly affect the matter.
Last but not least, the level of isolation that the job demands or that its required should be mentioned too since some jobs need a more peaceful and focused atmosphere, in this case, office, such as a writter, an accountant, a boss...
while others might need merely a place to sit or a computer such as a secretary.
In conclusion, to sum up, I differ from the idea of working in small, overwhelming spaces, although I do not go along with the opened design ideas either.
I think that each job demands different conditions and the already mentioned points are the ones to take into consideration to decide that.
