The School of the Future Have you ever give a thought to the matter concerning how the school of the future will be?
It comes without saying that, every time we think of the future, technology has a significant role in it.
Distant though it may seem, the future is closer than ever, in the way that in the recent years there has been a sharp increase in the usage of technological devices among the population, so have in schools.
I cannot help but mention that, when it comes to picturing the school of the future, I always imagine a robot taking the teacher's place and computer screens everywhere.
Nevertheless, replacing a human teacher for a robot one would be a big mistake, from my humble opinion, due to the fact that human contact cannot be replaced by any gadgets.
Each and every student has a different personality and distinct needs, and only a real person is capable of adapting the study method to every individual.
On the contrary, I find that the rest of technological devices that could be introduced in the school system would have a positive impact on the students' learning as their principal aim is to make our lives easier.
So next time you stop and wonder how the future will be, you should have under consideration that human beings will have to be part of it, and nothing will ever substitute real feelings.
Thank for recommending me write Write and Improve.
I have found this tool to be quite useful.
I will start my description from the positive aspects and then move on to the flaws.
What I like the most about it is its levels of advancement.
It seems that developers thought about all English learners.
There are variety of writing tasks for each level which are related to everyday's situations.
Another interesting feature is the progress scale which helps you monitor your improvement rate.
However, feedback is the most confusing part.
Sentences with an errors are being highlited and you receive a short, written explanation.
On the one hand it's very detailed as even the lack of coma highlithes whole sentence.
On the other, the written explanation is useless and you have figure for yourself what have you done wrong.
I think that Write and Improve could improve a little.
Then it would be superior to all other learning methods.
I believe it depends on the teacher and I will happy to justify my answer.
Learning is like a hourney and a teacher is a students guide.
As long as the teacher can take the student where he wants to go, it's fine.
There is of course more to it.
The aspect of integrity is of a paramount importance.
For example, some teachers are only there for money, just doing their jobs. Whilst others are the true teachers, who cares about the student and his progress.
Some of the teachers are also disorganised and inordinate.
They seem to lost in the lecture and often forget about time.
It's like walking a long distance without taking a break.
It can be exhaustive to students and cause to loose enthusiasm.
On the other hand, I meet teachers who are willing to go the extra mile.
They have remained a students in a sense, are not afraid of questions, and are keen to investigate issues.
These are the teachers I like the most.
