'It drives me up the wall!',
said one student early this morning when he, sitting next to a computer screen, learned that all university students be advised to excersise thrice a week.
This notice was immediately understood as an abrasive and nosy by many students, but, not so surprisingly, there is a good reason for embedding this rule.
The research shows university student in general and computer nerds in particular are activity-deprived individuals with fitness level so poor it raises a red flag for their physicians.
Not only have some students stopped any excercising, but they substantially minimized their exposure to sun, fresh air, and shockingly, some of them even do not leave their dormitories any more.
Although the lockdown and curfew exacerbates the situation further, the real problem is mostly the inherent lazines of the students.
Therefore, the college council suggested mandatory sport activities at least three times a week for everyone.
Albeit justifiable, the decision triggers a question of personal freedome.
Can the council indeed force students to engage in sport activities?
Some argue this is simply illegal, and thus, impossible to do so.
But, this coin has another side as well.
The council is a body fully responsible for well-being of students and as such, it is entitled to take care of their mental and physical health.
Therefore, the above mentioned statement is conceivable.
Clearly, this non-trivial affair will ignite a fierce disputation in the next student assemblage.
But, given the ussual bland and boring discussions, it is a great achievement as well.
Our colleague Bend-Over shrewdly commented this situation is a lose-lose situation: students are mad at the council, therefore they will hesitate to excersise.
He gingerly sugested to encourage students' sport activity by providing them free access to the gym and the swimming pool.
