It's a common belief that learning to speak a foreign language has positive impact on our life.
And I think that it's more crucial in the 4.0 industry than it was in the past.
Firstly, learning foreign languages will meet the great demand of communicating of people.
We are living in the modern world where people easily interact with others through the continients thanks to the invention of Internet in 1969.
Besides, the need for travelling and trading is one of the reasons bring people together.
So, learning new languages helps people whose culture is different easily understand each other.
By that way, it becomes more and more necessary than in the past when people couldn't afford travelling or exchanging things with foreigners.
Moreover, today we have a new notion- global citizens; it is the idea that one's identity transcends geography or political borders and that responsibilities or rights are derived from membership in a broader class: "humanity."
Therefore, the priority is that they have ability to speak more than two languages.
Then, they can do their work and make a contribution to the development of their countries.
Nowadays it is well known that computers and tablets are winning popularity over the students and teachers.
However, I'm one of those who believe that we shouldn't remove the books.
I agree that computers have many perks, for instance with them we can search information with just a few clicks, and the sources of information we have on the internet are almost endless.
Nevertheless, these perks can be at the same time disadvantages.
It has been demostrated that computers and tablets can reduce our capacity of attention, for example many students use to spend most of their time in social applications such as Facebook and Instagram.
Due to this I think that books are still useful for students because with them we normally are more concentrated and therefore we can learn more.
I have to say that in some lessons the In conclusion, even though I believe that computers are vital for the schools and universities, we should keep using the books for some lessons.
Studying abroad has advantages as well as disadvantages.
The main advantage is that students have the opportunity of exploring other cultures while purseing their studies abroad.
Learning about other cultures is a real surplus in the nowadays multicultural society, this will with no doubt be a big advantage during their future careers.
They will learn about the cultural background and differences, will learn how to relate to other cultures, certainly skills they wouldn't have been able to develop during a study in their own country.
Another advantage is that if a student decided that studying abroad is an option, then that student is able to choose from multiple qualified universities and available degree programmes.
Taking a study in a foreign country will also be a big asset on their resumees.
The biggest disadvantage is, while focussing on their study, the students will also have to take care of their of their own household, while at the same time live in a foreign country, not aware of the cultural differences, which might cause problems and probably being able to make them selves understood because they do not master the foreign language yet.
Studying abroad will, if you are not eligible for a grant, be far more expensive than studying at home.
Several types of grants are available to students and it might be worthywhile to explore the possibilities before deciding in which country you want to persue your study.
Living in another country makes it also more difficult to find a suitable parttime job to support yourself during your studies.
