Dear partecipants to the town council, I would like to express my opinion regarding the last idea about banning the use of cell phones in common areas such as restaurants and shops, as well as public transport.
I am actually aware of the environmental as well as biological risks of the pollution due to electromagnetic waves, and the very kittle worry of the people about that.
First of all because people do not 'feel' the electromagnetic waves, in the sense that it is a pollution that doesn't make noise, or bad smelling, nor even is 'seen' as wasted material.
Nevertheless, it is with no doubt acting on our ears warming, as the cell phone electromagnetic waves are of the same kind of the microwaves, thus enabling our water molecules to 'twist', producing warming as a secondary effect.
Unfortunately this kind of molecular movement is sometimes creating headaches or even tumors (most of the times benign).
Especially in young people, as they are made of much more water than adults.
For all these reasons I would agree with the council's initiative, for the 'precautionary principle' that would induce us not to use intensively cell phones before a clear scientific statistics is made by our healthy organization.
Anyway, before such a decision, I would encourage to take initiatives in order to make people discuss with competent doctors about the problem.
In fact I think that you need first of all to give the knowledge, than you can convince people to accept the rule.
Currently, few high schools presume students to proof a voluntary work in order to graduate.
But is this just a waste of time or does it promoting the personality development of its students?
At first, undeniabely most students experience schools as too theoratic rather than practical.
It seems to them that they learn something with low impact for their future.
Or do you have to acquire broadening skills - think about arts or sports - for applying to a maths degree?
Therefore, volunteers could gain real life experience, which would tops the dry school material off.
Additionally, students had to choose from a range of voluntary work that suits their interests best and learning essentially life lessons such as communicating with others or to be empathatic.
Lastly and not less relevant is that students with a voluntary background set themselves out from other peers.
This enables them to gain benefits in an apllication process for the university or a job.
To sum up I personally think that more schools should assume students to conduct work on a voluntary basis.
In my view this work would certainly broaden the horizen of the students academically and personally.
These paragraphs contain the question whether university students should live on their own while they are attending school or whether they should live at home.
I personally think that it is less laborious to stuy at home, because you do not need to seek for another affordable accomodation and you can spare your money due to a missing rent you do not need to pay.
To sum up this is a great choice if your degree course is taught at your home university.
Despite of that it is obvious that some prospective student moves away because of their interest in a specifit study field.
Furthermore, you will mature quicker by managing your own life, that covers the daily shopping in a supermarket or to arrange a doctor's appointment, and you will feel more confident suczessive.
Moreover it could be beneficial to study even abroad in order to learn a foreign language and to represent you as person with international attributes.
That would eases your job search after graduation enormally, if you woud prefer to study in an international working environment.
Since a well-known magazine for English language learners has asked for reviews about useful ressources for learning English I recommend Write & Improve with Cambridge whose function is to improve your writing skills step by step.
If you open this writing tool, you can choose between various tasks which require a differend level of English.
After that you start to write a text and hand it in after you finished.
Subsequently a review of your written text appears and you can see what you have done correctly and where you can improve.
Now you are correcting your mistakes and hand in your revised text to check whether it is right.
On the one hand this method requires a highly responsible and motivated student who seeks his mistakes over a long time, but on the other hand it can be extremly unsatisfied when you can not fix some mistakes.
So this tool is a quite good way to self-study.
But it is even better, when you can ask someone for help sometimes to improve your writings a lot.
In my view every English student should use this tool or a similiar to enhance your individual writing skills.
In more particular you can learn in your own speed and focus on your developing fields.
Nevertheless it can be frustrating to seek mistakes for a long time, but then you need to go on.
People around the world plan their life differently based on their wishes.
Two possible life plans are a long calm life and a short intense life.
Firstly, it is crucial for everybody to live as long as possible in order to be able of fulfilling every wish.
Referring to this, it is out of doubt that a long life suits best to this life goal, because the elderly spend more time on Earth and can look back at a long life span.
If anyone pursues to reach that, he needs to live healthy and to stand out of any danger.
Another life plan is to act less calmly and to do more exciting as well as dangerous things.
Moreover, they wish to do more dangerous activities because of the adrealine rush.
In more particular, some people feel more vital during these nastier situations and can relax from the monotony of their routined life.
In addition, these people think that they should do anything that they want before they get too old to do it.
While both of these life plans are imaginable for me, in my opinion a more calm life would fit better with my expectations.
In more detail, I am not a person that seeks exciting situations and I feel more comfortable in a structured dday routine.
But most important is that I want to live as long as possible, because I have several plans for my future.
Young people and sports Should be sport obligatory for young people?
Many would argue that not.
Others could see this from different perspective.
Let's try to take a look at both opinions.
According to statistics every fifth child has overweight in UK schools. "
Just sport more and ear less" could some people say.
But it's not that simple.
It's not easy to "just sport."
Young people can be disgussed by sport because of their early childhood memories.
For example Harry was forced to do atleast five sport activities a week, and none was interesting, nor enjoyable, for him.
Because of this now, when he can take some responsibility into his hands, he doen't do any sport, because he thinks all of them are alike.
On the other hand there are people like Sarah, who are finding their passion in the early childhood.
Nowadays she is basketball player in national league, playing atleast five times a week.
Although she wasn't forced to choose exceptionaly this sport, she found it thanks to PE in school, where sports were changing almost every lesson.
This had fortunately led to her outstanding success.
Without a doubt is she role model for many young ones.
To summarize, this question is not as easy to answer as it may seem.
Seldom do we see as ambitious young people as Sarah.
But still her story tells us something.
She could've tried all the sport in her childhood and nobody was forcing her to do any of them.
Therefore she is sporting until now without planning to stop.
Other people don't have to be as active as her but finding any hobby in sports helps them in their healthy lifestyle.
All in all, I'm certaint that young people should try as much sport as possible, but forcing them to do what they don't like won't help the cause.
