Medical doctors and cities A great issue faced by many cities is the absence of health care staff, mostly medical doctors, in rural areas.
This problem affects both underdeveloped and developed countries.
Medical doctors do not want to live in countryside.
But why does it happen?
Which reason drive to that situation in several countries, being these countries rich or porr.
I guess there are several things that can influence on it.
One of them is when a professionalhigh qualificated as a doctor lives in big cities they can make more money.
In addition, doctors living in big cities can easily get educational updates such as MBA, courses and conferences rather them live in rural areas.
Living in main cities can help these doctors make professionals conections and that is very important for their careers.
Maybe they would not be able to get these opportunities if they lived in countyside.
Despite of the difficult of setting medical doctors in countryside, there are some possible strategies that towns can adopt in order to atract these professionals.
One is give to them taxes exemption to set new medical office.
Another possibility is offer advantages to just medical gradueted students.
I have seen an interesting alternative here in my country.
Medical schools are being setting in medium size cities, known as regional centers, and it has been helping fix young doctors in those areas.
Regional retention surveys has shown that it works.
