Beyond any doubt, the ideal state of affairs would be always telling the truth, no matter the subject.
Life in such a society would be far different from what we know in our own.
There would not be confidence crisis.
On the contrary, everybody could trust at everyone.
However, actually we are not prepared to such a pristine truth.
In many cases people see themselves compelled to lie in order to comply with social arrangements or etiquette.
Let's see some examples.
If someone asks about their own appearance, the answer will be invariably positive or, at least, not entirely negative, although we know that it is not always the case.
The same happens when we give opinions concerning feelings and performances.
In these situations we tend to mitigate and ornament the truth, what is not the same thing that being polite.
Politeness and truth are not antinonims.
This confusion is a common error.
You can do both.
However, as previously mentioned, since we are not ready to remove social conventions when they colide with truth, some small "white lies" ended up becoming necessary.
Using the same example above: wether you answer "you are ugly," certainly somebody's feelings will be hurt.
It is better to avoid that.
Perusing veracity at all cost does not pay off yet.
Nonetheless, I believe that one day, when we have learned to be more emotionally matured, the truth will reign undisputed.
Nowadays companies are concerned about work environment, and therefore, there is a debate about whether offices should be open or enclosed spaces.
Open designs are superior because of promoting friendly work places and discouraging competition.
A open-space office develops a healthy work environment.
In fact, cubicles without walls encourage workers to co-operate between them due to the lack of communication barriers, making the work environment friendly.
For example, these open designs are allowed tech-companies to improve their performance and productivity.
Another point to have into account is that open-spaces might reduce hierarchy levels between workers because of the concept of sharing the space.
Some detractors of this open-office layouts claim that could be reduce productivity.
Although being in contact with everybody ,without physical restrictions, could lead to excessive lost of time, there is a great deal of evidence in favour.
For example, it has been recognised that productivity is linked with healthy work environments, and as a consequence, better work performance is related to proper team work.
In conclusion, there are many advantages to open-offices such as co-operative environment and reduction of hierarchy, which are reflected on high productivity.
The future of architecture is open spaces, in public and private sectors.
