It is argued that today's teens are the less active generation in the past decades.
This statement is sustained not only by the increasing number of young people with different illnesses associated to obesity but also by the worrying amount of fast food businesses, which raises year by year.
I believe we should all be aware of the negative consequences an unhealthy died might cause us and try moving out of the comfort zones, which we are so familiar with.
Although it might seem a drastic measure, I am profoundly to urge teenagers and students to attend sport classes at least three times a week, for their own benefit.
I will sustain my view with multiple arguments.
Firstly, the actual syllabus seems to be insufficient to ensure a proper balance between in class or outside sport activities and a healty life education.
The coach is usually focused on following the school programme.
If the amount of classes are to be raised, he would be more willing to diverse the educational programme, therefore some nutrition advice or examples of exercises to be done at home might be of his interest.
Then, the students could be determined to take part in additional sport competitions, if they would feel they are enough prepared for.
More rehearsal means more self-confidence.
And a well trained teenager is more likely to become a professional sportive.
Another important factor is the self-esteem the teenager could improve, by reshaping their body within the sports room.
Some might argue that if someone wants to lose weight, then it's up to him, but in reality is very challenging and difficult to stick to the plan, if he is on his own.
A class group engaged in sport activities would be far more effective and efficient, with visible results.
Sport's beneficials to young people are undeniable and the entitled authorities should play their part in supporting them.
