I certainly agree on the fact that youngs should do sports, as well as all the people during their life.
An active lifestyle has positive effects on anyone, both on the physical health than on mental health.
I don't even think that both children than university students should be forced to do three hours of sports per week.
I would let the families choose the combination, taking into account a lot of different situations, as well as the different characteristics of their sons.
First of all, I think that school should treat gymn as another subject, and should account for it at least two hours per week, but all together, that is to say: students should have time to change clothes, and to have showers afterwards.
Two hours together would be enough to have an hour of effective sport or gymn and an hour for changing (equipped bathrooms should be provided in any school).
Later on, I suggest that each school should organize extra curriculum courses of sports in order to group those students that are most interested, at a very low extra charge.
Finally, families could follow or not the teachers advice of making or not extra courses, depending on their sons ability in the sport itself.
In this sense I think that families should have the freedom to choose, also because sometimes they prefer to have children engaged in other activities, like music courses or other community social activities, or simply studying more.
For what regards students at the university, finally, I think that they should be absolutely free to choose how to spend their time.
They are enough mature to understand if they need or not some physical activity, and the activity could just be a walk in the city park rather than a precise sport activity.
