It is an intriguing question: better short but intense life or long but calm and 'grey', and with no bright colors ?
I think that, even if it seems hard to decide, at a closer look maybe most people believe that they would prefer a short but intense life.
And probably it is mainly for one reason: the intensity of the feelings that a totally involving experience carries on with it, in a special way carries on a time distortion.
That is to say, time passes very slowly when you are going throughout a very intense experience.
You remember every minute of the time passed, and every minute lasts as a day long.
This is a result from the psychology science: the time is not absolute but has a different duration from one to another, with respect to his or her feeling of the time.
Our mental processes enhance some situation, and they thus appear longer than other moments of poor mental activity.
And those special situations, despite their real duration, are thus impressed in our mind that they appear much longer in time.
And we can understand the common phrase "better a day as a lion than one hundred as a ship."
It is the sensation of having spent intensively all the time in your hands, no one second lost, that makes you happier.
And we all would like to have good time.
Good time is not more time, but better one.
