A large number of studies indicate that obesity problems are rising nowadays.
This is a big headache for public health and it is necessary to educate people about this matter.
However, forcing people to do exercise could be counterproductive.
On one hand, we must stimulate a more active lifestyle and introduce a subject in school and Universities seem to be the right choice.
Younger generations will be more educated about their health and, as a consequence, could raise awareness among their family members and everyone will benefit.
But, on the other hand, forcing young people to do exercise when they do not want to, or feel embrassed about it, could create a contrary effect: generate distance on physical activity.
Kids and young people are ruthless and not everyone is good at sports.
We must be careful because bullying is also a big public issue in our schools.
We do not want to create another issue in our schools.
I agree on incentive a more healthy lifestyle for children and college students, nonetheless, this can not be by forcing sports activities.
We must find different ways to introduce a more healthy lifestyle.
For instance, we could educate and incentive by rising college credit for those who do sports in schools.
In other matter, changing the kind of food we give to children in school casinos to a more healthy one could also be a good idea.
As for University students, I think establishing more healthy casinos and restaurants on campus is the right way.
Also, reducing college debt repayments for those who have taken some type of sport during their university times could motivate sports activities on campus.
There are many ways to awareness of a more healthy lifestyle for young people, forcing sports shouldn't be one of them.
