The question of if computers and tablets should completely replace books in schools and universities gains popularity owing to advancement of electronic books.
Fortunately, renowned experts have a precise answer for this query.
In order to learn what it is, please proceed to next paragraph.
In their view, this suggestion shouldn't be put on action due to the fact that e-books are quite vulnerable to power outages and corruptions.
To illustrate, all digital textbooks could be hacked in matter of seconds, disabling education hazardously for couple of weeks.
Therefore, this kind of data always requires substitute resources such as books, no matter how bulky they are.
However, it doesn't mean that we must discard traditional books entirely.
After all, they have numerous advantages: First and foremost, they don't use up much space.
Furthermore, they greatly reduce deforestation levels.
And last but not least, they are easier to carry around.
In conclusion, I would argue that computers and tablets should be combined with traditional books instead of replacing them completely in schools and universities.
The more the gap between the rich and the poor grows, the more alluring wealth becomes.
This state of affairs reminds us of the old saying: It is more important to be healthy than to be rich.
With the aim of solving this dilemma, the relationship between health and money will be covered in the essay.
Obviously, money can't cure all of the diseases.
To illustrate, in spite of being heavily funded, oncologysts haven't found an effective treatment for cancer yet.
Furthermore, there is a plethora of fatal rare diseases waiting their cure.
And as expected, they don't care about the one's social status.
On the other hand, it can't be denied that money possesses a profound effect on our health.
That is to say, maintaning health requires costly needs such as a clean and secure shelter, hygen and healthcare infrafracture, a balanced diet etc.
Besides, some research suggest that wealthier patients usually receive more efficient treatments.
In conclusion, I would argue that wealth is superior to health due to the fact that it maintains health, though it isn't always the case.
