On the one hand, zapping books at schools and colleges is an impossible task.
It is a matter of fact that we now are in the heyday of the information highway, but this does not mean the physical books demise.
It is necessary to remember that not each school over the country is in the high echelons of richness.
There are thousands and thousands of students unable to have proper facilities conducive to learning.
The underdog lives on the edge of society.
There are people unable to buy either top-notch tablets, cutting edge computers, or suntuous technologies.
What is more, many do not even can afford proper food or necessities.
On the other hand, if society is someday able to provide the proper conditions to live to all people, it would be a conducive scenation to chanbe physical books to digital.
Nevertheless, it does not means that all physical books would disappear, only text books are due to make it.
There are a lot of individuals attached to have the real thing and enjoy deluxe and hardcover editions.
Colleges would benefit of format changes because they would have access to update information always.
Telling the truth is obviously essential.
When we were children, we have been taught not to tell lies, because it is wrong.
Besides, a person caught while telling a lie will never be trusted again.
Therefore, it seems that always telling the truth is important.
But I don't quite agree with this idea.
In my opinion, telling the truth should always be prefered to tell a lie.
However, there are a few situations, where telling a lie enables to preserve a good relationship, or the sensibility of a person.
For instance, telling someone who's asking you wheter his son died in an accident or not that indeed, the son is dead is maybe not the best way to proceed.
Rather than saying a brutal, violent truth which may shock or deseperate someone, a soft lie which leads to the truth could help this person to cope with this event when she'll learn about it.
To lie should never be accepted, except in the occasions where it's in a view to conceal an hard, desperating truth, or when it leads in a softer way to the truth.
Moreover, some line of business require if not lies, a certain concealment of the truth.
In politics for instance, telling all the truth can be devastating for a faction which used backdoors to have their candidat elected.
To conclude, it is essential to always tell the truth, except in the few situations where it is better to make a small concealment of a shocking truth.
That's a fact, the school that we know today, is about to disappear.
Many research conclude that our current way of schooling, was created in the industrial era, where people need to be guided all the steps, with passive way of learning, which is basic absorbing content a source.
The content in this case, is defined by a educational curriculum, and is passed by a figure of a teacher or professor depending what enviroment you are.
With the advance of technology, other skill, and abilities are demand from people to being able to perform, and pursue a working career.
But how to prepare people from this new world?
In my opinion, the School of the future, needs to focus on teach people to learn how to learn.
Today, with the internet, we don't need anymore a figure of a teacher as we know, but instead a mentor, who will guide a student what to learn, and how to learn.
We need to teach our kids to be self learners, who independently will search for knowledge, adapting their own needs.
